22,IssuesEvent,2016-03-19 14:32:58+00:00,46566669,jaraco/irc,1573352,JonasT,,,opened,"RPL_MYINFO / RPL_ISUPPORT needed for chanmodes with parameters instead of hardcoded ""bklohvq""",[],[],0,"A note first: this ticket is based on taking a look at https://github.com/jaraco/irc/blob/master/irc/modes.py
If that is outdated/unused code, this ticket is probably invalid and should be ignored.

It appears that the irclib doesn't correctly handle MODE parsing: it seems to assume a hardcoded set of ""bklvohq"" for channel modes with parameters. However, this can lead to all sorts of problems with modern IRC daemons that introduce additional modes.

The correct behavior would be:

1. Instead of the current single hardcoded set ""bklvohq"", always use two whereas one contains the modes that have parameters when they are added (+), and the other modes that have parameters when removed(-) in a MODE event.

2. Check 005 RPL_iSUPPORT for the CHANMODES=.... parameter. (see http://www.irc.org/tech_docs/005.html ) The set of channel modes with parameters should be set to A, B, C (see link) for modes that are added, and A, B for modes that are removed.

3. If there's no CHANMODES in 005, assume 004 RPL_MYINFO numeric syntax `<server> <ver> <usermode> <chanmode> <chanmodes with parameters> ... `     (the <chanmodes with parameters> parameter and possible further additional ones are not in the original spec, but added by 99% of modern IRC servers - also see here https://www.alien.net.au/irc/irc2numerics.html ) and exact `<chanmodes with parameters>`. Use this set both for modes that are added and removed in a MODE event (that is an approximation, but you can't do any better). 

4. Use the two newly introduced sets instead of ""bklvohq"" for parsing MODE events.

Otherwise, you're bound to run into trouble parsing some more complex mode events on modern servers.

",{},{}
