531,IssuesEvent,2018-04-14 15:34:29+00:00,28530868,cannatag/ldap3,1319333,cannatag,,,closed,pwdLastSet Attribute cannot be set to 0,"[{'id': 725837142, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cannatag/ldap3/labels/Fixed%20In%20upcoming%20version', 'name': 'Fixed In upcoming version', 'color': '63e28e', 'default': False}, {'id': 161142985, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cannatag/ldap3/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],5,"It appears that after the most recent change (2.4.1) was pushed, pwdLastSet cannot be set to 0, which is a valid non-timestamp value for Active Directory. Issue #471 references the same issue but for the -1 value, and while the fix for that was shipped in the most recent build, it seems to have caused the 0 value to be rejected. 

0 remains a valid value for the pwdLastSet attribute - ref https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa746510(v=vs.85).aspx

The following code preforms as expected with ldap3==2.4.0:
`set_pls = {""pwdLastSet"": (ldap3.MODIFY_REPLACE, [""0""])}
self.connection.modify(distinguished_name, set_pls)
`

However, with ldap3==2.4.1, the same code throws an LDAPException ""value '0' non valid for attribute 'pwdLastSet'""

Thanks!",{},{}
534,IssuesEvent,2017-09-19 06:12:36+00:00,28530868,cannatag/ldap3,722068,mkemmerling,,,opened,v2.3 breaks MockBaseStrategy,[],[],0,"[Commit 04adf56: fixed regression with newer version of pyasn1 ](https://github.com/cannatag/ldap3/commit/04adf569fecdcbb822783f1b5e1c275285e2373c#diff-0fcbc648a57c341479b5f8a1bf1bec2d) changed line 810 in _ldap3/strategy/mockBase.py_ to check for the existence of the 'initial' key in `node.assertion` before accessing it:

```
-            if node.assertion['initial']:
+            if 'initial' in node.assertion and node.assertion['initial'] is not None:
```
and similarly for the 'any' and 'final' keys in line 815 and 819.

But in line 822 the 'any' and 'final' keys are still accessed withot checking for their existence first:

```
            if substring_filter and not node.assertion['any'] and not node.assertion['final']:  # only initial, adds .*
```
which results in a KeyError if the 'any' or 'final' key is not present.

Changing this to

```
            if substring_filter and not node.assertion.get('any', None) and not node.assertion.get('final', None):  # only initial,adds .*
```
fixes the problem.",{},{}
538,IssuesEvent,2017-09-12 18:50:48+00:00,28530868,cannatag/ldap3,3577694,mikebarris,,,opened,Recommendations for using connection pooling with frequent rebinds.,[],[],0,"Hi,

This is just a question so hopefully this is the correct place to submit it.

We are looking for recommendations to minimize our open connections to LDAP. Our current configuration involves using pooled connections bound with a service account to make numerous calls to access data contained in our LDAP server. Additionally, we also use the LDAP server to authenticate users. To authenticate users we establish a new connection and attempt to bind with that users uname and password. This current flow causes problems because it establishes many connections to the LDAP server and we would rather utilize the pool since SSL handshakes and other TCP transactions have already been established. One idea is to rebind the pooled connection with the new user report success and then rebind back to the service account.

When reviewing the code rebinding on a pooled connection will be difficult because of two main hurdles.

- When calling rebind on a reusable pooled connection the code iterates over each worker and rebinds with the new user and password. This seems dangerous in our situation since all the connections in the pool will no longer be associated with the service account originally setup and now be bound to the user and password for the one authentication attempt. The fear is in high volume situations requests may come in before rebinding may occur.

- Rebind also appears to be lazy loaded by design which is great feature except we need to rely on a subsequent call to get the results of the bind. This feels problematic in high volume pooled instances.

Thanks for reviewing. Have you encountered any similar flows with the library? Do you have any recommendations to handle our use case?
",{},{}
