986,IssuesEvent,2017-04-05 06:50:54+00:00,20101515,giampaolo/psutil,754175,qris,,,opened,"Process.io_counters() fails randomly on Linux with ""need more than 1 value to unpack""",[],[],0,"This happened once so far, at process startup, so it seems to be random:

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
...
    return self._process.io_counters()
  File ""/remote/install/sw/external/20170403-0-64/lib/python2.7/site-packages/psutil-5.2.1-py2.7-linux-x86_64.egg/psutil/__init__.py"", line 787, in io_counters
    return self._proc.io_counters()
  File ""/remote/install/sw/external/20170403-0-64/lib/python2.7/site-packages/psutil-5.2.1-py2.7-linux-x86_64.egg/psutil/_pslinux.py"", line 1320, in wrapper
    return fun(self, *args, **kwargs)
  File ""/remote/install/sw/external/20170403-0-64/lib/python2.7/site-packages/psutil-5.2.1-py2.7-linux-x86_64.egg/psutil/_pslinux.py"", line 1451, in io_counters
    name, value = line.split(b': ')
ValueError: need more than 1 value to unpack
```

It looks like a Linux bug, because if I cat `/proc/self/io` (a freshly started process) then I see a blank line at the end (which could cause this error):

```
$ cat /proc/self/io
rchar: 2012
wchar: 0
syscr: 7
syscw: 0
read_bytes: 0
write_bytes: 0
cancelled_write_bytes: 0

```

Whereas if I look at an established process, I see no blank line at the end:

```
$ cat /proc/75051/io
rchar: 369142
wchar: 17779
syscr: 161
syscw: 13
read_bytes: 16384
write_bytes: 16384
cancelled_write_bytes: 0
```

It should be fairly easy to make psutil robust to this?",{},{}
