1176,IssuesEvent,2016-03-01 01:34:47+00:00,46906439,diafygi/acme-tiny,520459,rspeed,,,opened,Simplifying Testing,[],[],0,"Running the current testing setup was very challenging, and I ran into a lot of issues implementing it. Even after getting everything set up correctly, I frequently ran into errors caused by what I assume to be race conditions. Specifically, the GET request would arrive at the server *before* the POST request.

I had an idea that should simplify things quite a bit, but before I do a PR I want to make sure this would actually work with Travis (which I don't use).

Rather than running a script on the host, I set up a simple reverse proxy. The configuration for Nginx is only a few lines long. Locally I have the test runner spawn a subprocess which sets up a simple HTTP server. It works really well, and because it's just serving files from the temp folder, there's no need for Fuse and no race condition. Plus, as a bonus, it makes the setup extremely simple for anyone running the tests on a machine that can directly respond to LE.",{},{}
