2327,IssuesEvent,2017-11-02 12:08:43+00:00,10102813,lepture/flask-oauthlib,746323,dmayo3,,,opened,Handle empty error responses from OAuth APIs,[],[],0,"We're using this library with a 3rd party OAuth API.

Sometimes we get an error response back from their API that appears to have an empty response body but supplies `Content-Type: application/json`. This leads to a parsing error.

Clearly the API is behaving badly and I've filed an issue with them, but it should be possible for Flask OAuthlib to tolerate this scenario or enable the developer to suppress automatic parsing on a per request-basis.

It looks like it's possible to configure flask-oauthlib to override the Content-Type to text/plain and thus probably workaround the issue. However, this is done an construction time and so affects all requests in the application that use the same object.

Here is the relevant portion of the trace we get:

```
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/flask_oauthlib/client.py"", line 390, in get
  return self.request(*args, **kwargs)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/flask_oauthlib/client.py"", line 478, in request
  return OAuthResponse(resp, content, self.content_type)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/flask_oauthlib/client.py"", line 166, in __init__
  content_type=content_type,
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/flask_oauthlib/client.py"", line 122, in parse_response
  return json.loads(content)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/flask/json.py"", line 146, in loads
  return _json.loads(s, **kwargs)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/simplejson/__init__.py"", line 533, in loads
  return cls(encoding=encoding, **kw).decode(s)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/simplejson/decoder.py"", line 370, in decode
  obj, end = self.raw_decode(s)
File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/simplejson/decoder.py"", line 400, in raw_decode
  return self.scan_once(s, idx=_w(s, idx).end())
simplejson.scanner.JSONDecodeError: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)
```",{},{}
2340,IssuesEvent,2018-05-08 15:51:03+00:00,60546709,nithinmurali/pygsheets,20406663,DavisTownsend,,,closed,"RequestError: Timeout : timeout('The read operation timed out',)",[],[],0,"I have a script that is pulling around 200 google sheets within a for loop in python using the get_as_df() function. The script is configured to run nightly on a remote server from Jenkins. For some reason sometimes when it runs I will randomly get this error:
RequestError: Timeout : timeout('The read operation timed out',)

Usually when I rebuild it works fine. I have upped my google drive and google sheets API quotas and made my script sleep in between loops to make sure I'm not overloading the system with API requests so i don't think that's the issue, and it also retries 5 times if the read operation fails.

Do you know what's going on here or what this error is in relation to?",{},{}
2342,IssuesEvent,2015-07-08 14:01:09+00:00,12162812,prmtl/appfy.recipe.gae,638073,Trii,,,opened,Stand alone App Engine SDK is going away,[],[],0,"I received this email early today. Looks like gcloud will be the only way to do it going forward.

```
From: 'Andrew Jessup' via App Engine Managed VMs <app-engine-managed-vms@googlegroups.com>
Date: Wed, Jul 8, 2015, 3:17 AM
Subject: Upcoming changes to App Engine support in the Google Cloud SDK
To: app-engine-managed-vms@googlegroups.com <app-engine-managed-vms@googlegroups.com>


Hi folks,

We're making an important change to the Google Cloud SDK to simplify how App Engine developers can access and work with the SDK.

As of the next release, 0.9.68, of the Google Cloud SDK - we will no longer be distributing the stand alone App Engine SDKs. 

The gcloud preview app deploy and gcloud preview app run commands that most developers use within gcloud will continue to work, users should not notice any obvious change.

For users who were directly using appcfg.py, appcfg.sh, dev_appserver.py or dev_appserver.sh scripts, or the GUI launchers that were bundled with the Google Cloud SDK, you have two options:

You can continue to use the latest versions of these tools used by installing them from the stand-alone App Engine SDKs that can be found here: https://cloud.google.com/appengine/downloads.

In the short term, if you need to prevent this from happening, you can pin a version of gcloud SDK with the following commands:

  gcloud config set --scope=installation component_manager/fixed_sdk_version 0.9.67 
  gcloud components update

As part of this change, the gae-java, gae-python, gae-php, and gae-go components no longer exist in the component manager.  The `gcloud preview app run` command will install language specific runtime libraries on demand, as needed by your application.

If you have questions or concerns, please let us know.

Thanks,

Andrew, on behalf of the Cloud SDK team
```",{},{}
