2758,IssuesEvent,2016-09-14 00:32:11+00:00,27742208,jschneier/django-storages,2245080,jschneier,,,closed,svg mimetype for S3 content-type,[],[],4,"Hi,
Is there a recommended method for setting the content-type headers for .svg files on S3 to `image/svg+xml`?

Python 2.7 up to 2.7.11 doesn't have the mimetype so we get the default `application/octet-stream` on S3 (None result from `mimetypes.guess_type`)

The following code in s3boto.py works in order to register the image/svg+xml mimetype and set the content-type header.  Is this the best solution or am I missing something?

```
*** s3boto.py   2016-03-17 17:24:07.836025937 +0000
--- s3boto.py.mimetype  2016-03-17 17:23:23.639031962 +0000
***************
*** 207,212 ****
--- 207,213 ----
      secret_key = setting('AWS_S3_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY', setting('AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY'))
      file_overwrite = setting('AWS_S3_FILE_OVERWRITE', True)
      headers = setting('AWS_HEADERS', {})
+     mimetypes = {}
      bucket_name = setting('AWS_STORAGE_BUCKET_NAME')
      auto_create_bucket = setting('AWS_AUTO_CREATE_BUCKET', False)
      default_acl = setting('AWS_DEFAULT_ACL', 'public-read')
***************
*** 247,252 ****
--- 248,256 ----
              if hasattr(self, name):
                  setattr(self, name, value)

+         for name, value in self.mimetypes.items():
+             mimetypes.add_type(name, value)
+
          # For backward-compatibility of old differing parameter names
          if acl is not None:
              self.default_acl = acl
```
Then include the additional mimetype settings in the S3BotoStorage lamda function:

```
    mimetypes={
        'image/svg+xml': '.svg',
    },
```

",{},{}
