4129,IssuesEvent,2018-07-03 09:38:37+00:00,41542605,biolab/orange3-prototypes,919223,thocevar,555189,biolab,opened,Pseudotime inference,[],[],0,"Implement a widget for inference of pseudotime based on the minimum spanning tree approach already implemented as a prototype script.

The prototype implementation is available at https://github.com/thocevar/orange3-prototypes/blob/mst/orangecontrib/prototypes/pseudotime.py. It consists of the following steps (similar to the TSCAN method):
1. Perform dimensionality reduction with PCA.
2. Use k-means to cluster the data points and determine the centroids.
3. Construct a minimum spanning tree of centroids (Prim's O(n^2) algorithm).
4. Find the diameter of the MST (longest path/backbone, see https://cs.stackexchange.com/questions/11263/longest-path-in-an-undirected-tree-with-only-one-traversal).
5. Project the data points onto tree edges (section ""Cell ordering and pseudo-time calculation"" in the TSCAN paper).
6. Visualize the tree and projections in the space of the first two PCA components.

The task is to convert the prototype into an Orange widget:
- Design the widget.
  - Visualization should be similar to the one in the prototype.
  - Determine an appropriate set of parameters in the control panel: number of PCA components, number of clusters, coloring of points by a specified attribute (e.g. class value), drawing of projection lines on/off, etc.
  - Interactivity (selecting subsets of points, selecting points by choosing a MST vertex or edge) or at least the possibility of adding it is a plus.
- Restructure and modularize the code. The basic method should be separate from the visualization/widget. Consider a
  - MST class for construction of minimum spanning tree and finding the diameter. Use the implemented Prim's algorithm for this task (we might want to add Kruskal later for any other use cases),
  - Pseudotime class for tasks such as projection of points onto tree edges and computation of pseudotime of projected points (e.g. based on their distances or just by ordering them).

Reference:
- Ji, Zhicheng, and Hongkai Ji. ""TSCAN: Pseudo-time reconstruction and evaluation in single-cell RNA-seq analysis."" Nucleic acids research 44.13 (2016): e117-e117.",{},{}
