5381,IssuesEvent,2018-07-24 11:09:21+00:00,81349068,snipsco/snips-nlu,1119660,McFoggy,2564618,snipsco,opened,expose 'transformed' rawValue for numbers,[],[],0,"as exposed in #636 sometime if you want to print back recognized values you need to have a raw representation of the float value in a slot.

When the input contains already a ""string number"" representation of the value like below with `""rawValue"": ""12.7""` it is possible to round the numerical value at the same number of expected decimals than the ones provided inside the input:
```
{
    ""range"": {
        ""start"": 16,
        ""end"": 20
    },
    ""rawValue"": ""12.7"",
    ""value"": {
        ""kind"": ""Number"",
        ""value"": 12.699999809265137
    },
    ""entity"": ""snips/number"",
    ""slotName"": ""data""
}
```

But when the input is in the form `""rawValue"": ""twelve dot seven""`, it becomes difficult to do the rounding correctly
```
{
    ""range"": {
        ""start"": 16,
        ""end"": 32
    },
    ""rawValue"": ""twelve dot seven"",
    ""value"": {
        ""kind"": ""Number"",
        ""value"": 12.699999809265137
    },
    ""entity"": ""snips/number"",
    ""slotName"": ""data""
}
```

Would it be possible to extend the data model to introduce some kind of `rawNumberValue` or `rawInterpretedValue` either at the _slot_ level or at the _slot.value_ level like in the following example:

```
{
    ""range"": {
        ""start"": 16,
        ""end"": 32
    },
    ""rawValue"": ""twelve dot seven"",
    ""value"": {
        ""kind"": ""Number"",
        ""rawNumberValue"": ""12.7"",
        ""value"": 12.699999809265137
    },
    ""entity"": ""snips/number"",
    ""slotName"": ""data""
}
```
",{},{}
5406,IssuesEvent,2017-04-27 09:31:44+00:00,24213271,adobe-type-tools/afdko,2119742,miguelsousa,2768660,adobe-type-tools,closed,A .designspace document produced by fontmake is not accepted by AFDKO’s makeInstancesUFO ,[],"[{'login': 'miguelsousa', 'id': 2119742, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/2119742?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/miguelsousa', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/miguelsousa/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",2,"A .designspace document generated from .glyphs source using fontmake is refused by makeInstancesUFO as it does not include `postscriptFontName` attribute for each instance. As @anthrotype noted: this should be optional, at least according to https://github.com/LettError/designSpaceDocument

Perhaps AFDKO could infer the `postscriptFontName` from other attributes if this is not provided? It would be nice if AFDKO and fontmake played well together by default.

Maybe new AFDKO does not have a problem with that, I have not tried that yet.

See also https://github.com/googlei18n/fontmake/issues/306
",{},{}
5409,IssuesEvent,2017-11-15 18:10:14+00:00,24213271,adobe-type-tools/afdko,2856984,readroberts,2768660,adobe-type-tools,closed,fontTools version can contain str info,[],[],2,"see https://github.com/adobe-type-tools/afdko/blob/master/FDK/Tools/SharedData/FDKScripts/buildCFF2VF.py#L901

in this case Im running a ""cutting edge version"" so it has the extension `dev0`
a quick fix:

```python
from fontTools import varLib, version as fontToolsVersion

parts  = fontToolsVersion.split('.')
parts = [int(part) for part in parts if part.isdigit()]
print parts
```",{},{}
