5535,IssuesEvent,2016-02-12 16:14:01+00:00,11031844,uqfoundation/dill,321534,mmckerns,2855931,uqfoundation,opened,dill.detect.bad* fails to work under name-mangling,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/uqfoundation/dill/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],0,"There's a corner case (see here: http://stackoverflow.com/a/35360388/2379433) where `dill.detect.bad*` fails to detect what causes the pickling error.  In short, it's an override of `__getattribute__` that does name-mangling… so it's a real corner case, but worth thinking about.",{},{}
5537,IssuesEvent,2017-07-16 15:58:41+00:00,11017847,uqfoundation/pathos,5595494,erp12,2855931,uqfoundation,opened,ProcessingPool.map() hangs on KeyboardInterrupt,[],[],0,"When I send a `KeyboardInterrupt` while a `ProcessingPool.map()` is being called, a large scramble of stack trace is printed and my terminal hangs indefinitely. I can see all processes are still present int the activity monitor, and I have to kill the master python process.

I am on OSX using `pathos` 0.2.1 and I can recreate this behavior consistently in python 2.7 and python 3.5.

Below I have listed the class method where I initialize the pool, and the class method where I call `map()`.

```py
from pathos.multiprocessing import ProcessingPool as Pool

class Foo:

    ...

    def init_executor(self):
        if self.n_jobs == 1:
            return

        if self.n_jobs == -1:
            self.pool = Pool()
        else:
            self.pool = Pool(self.n_jobs)

    def _evaluate_population(self, X, y):
        def f(i):
            if not hasattr(i, 'error_vector'):
                return self._evaluate_individual(i, X, y)
            return i

        if hasattr(self, 'pool'):
            self.population[:] = self.pool.map(f, self.population)
        else:
            for i in self.population:
                f(i)
```
Am I doing something incorrectly? I have seen [an issue](http://bugs.python.org/issue8296) that indicates this is an issue in python's multiprocessing library as well. If this is a known issue, is there a workaround? Thanks in advance.",{},{}
5542,IssuesEvent,2015-12-21 02:16:11+00:00,2336578,twbs/bootstrap-sass,419884,cvrebert,2918581,twbs,closed,container-fixed mixin not respecting width variables,[],[],2,"The container-fixed mixin, when used, doesn't take into account the various screen size variables that are included in the variables file. It only takes into account the gutter size. Adding this to the mixin solves the problem.

  @media (min-width: $screen-sm-min) {
    width: $container-sm;
  }
  @media (min-width: $screen-md-min) {
    width: $container-md;
  }
  @media (min-width: $screen-lg-min) {
    width: $container-lg;
  }",{},{}
