5702,IssuesEvent,2016-11-06 21:39:24+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,Integrate the native engine release into the release script.,"[{'id': 268094252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 472006774, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/native', 'name': 'native', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}, {'id': 176601408, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/publishing', 'name': 'publishing', 'color': 'eb6420', 'default': False}]",[],0,The script will need to build binaries for at least linux/x86_64 and OSX as well as probably linux/i386.  In addition it will need to learn upload to bintray.,{},{}
5715,IssuesEvent,2015-06-01 22:06:21+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,119728,ericzundel,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,Filter `No processor claimed any of these annotations: ` from zinc output when compiling Java,[],[],1,"In the twitter Compiler wrapper used with Jmake, there is an option to filter warnings using a regular expression.  This is used to suppress one error from javac in particular:

```
[warn] warning: No processor claimed any of these annotations: ...
```

In our environment, these warnings come out on almost every invocation of javac, which is a lot now that we've turned on the 'isolated' compile strategy.",{},{}
5738,IssuesEvent,2017-11-27 18:29:33+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,usability issues with --changed-parent=HEAD,"[{'id': 22426646, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}, {'id': 268094252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 602506394, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/needs-cherrypick', 'name': 'needs-cherrypick', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],8,"In some cases I'd like to be able to make a bunch of changes in my repo, then compile just the targets that are changed.  I've been playing with --changed-parent=HEAD and while it works in some cases, it gives errors in other cases that prevent it from being effective.

For example, if I create a new file in a new directory (with no BUILD file), I get an error:

    mkdir bin
    echo ""hi"" > bin/README.txt
    ./pants --changed-parent=HEAD list 
    Exception caught: (<class 'pants.engine.mapper.ResolveError'>)

    Exception message: Path ""bin"" contains no BUILD files.

If I delete a directory with a BUILD file, I also get an error that the BUILD file doesn't exist (it doesn't anymore).

If I change a source file that is referenced by an existing BUILD file, it works as expected (listing/compiling the target affected).

I would expect if I delete a directory/file, or modify/add a file somewhere that's not referenced by a pants build, pants would just ignore these changes and list/compile any remaining targets that are modified.


",{},{}
5747,IssuesEvent,2018-08-16 06:33:50+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,14852634,Eric-Arellano,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,PEX behaving differently on Python 3 for `python_eval.py`,[],[],0,"## problem
Several of the tests are supposed to raise errors, but aren’t, such as https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/contrib/python/tests/python/pants_test/contrib/python/checks/tasks/test_python_eval.py#L180

We isolated it to this line https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/contrib/python/src/python/pants/contrib/python/checks/tasks/python_eval.py#L168. `pex.run()` is returning status code 0 in Py3, when it should be 1.

## Things not an issue

#### Stdout
We override stdout in `pex.run()`, which I thought would cause issues because `stdout` takes bytes in Py2 but unicode in Py3. No longer passing the parameters doesn’t work though.

#### Interpreter mismatch
the `interpreter` arg to `PEX()` and `PEXBuilder()` is for 2.7, but for `pex_info.build_properties` it’s 3

I thought this mismatch would cause issues? But I changed `python_setup.py` to require py3, which makes `interpreter` be py3, and it still fails.

#### Pex 1.4.5
Using this version vs. others isn't the breaking point.

## Issue is likely how PEX is built
@wisechengyi found that after the PEX is built, it doesn't matter which interpreter you use. If the PEX was created with Python 2, it will always work. If it was created with Python 3, it will never work.

To reproduce, apply this diff
```
diff --git a/contrib/python/src/python/pants/contrib/python/checks/tasks/python_eval.py b/contrib/python/src/python/pants/contrib/python/checks/tasks/python_eval.py
index 393df7a..7a19dc4 100644
--- a/contrib/python/src/python/pants/contrib/python/checks/tasks/python_eval.py
+++ b/contrib/python/src/python/pants/contrib/python/checks/tasks/python_eval.py
@@ -158,7 +158,8 @@ class PythonEval(LintTaskMixin, ResolveRequirementsTaskBase):
           pex_info.pex_path = ':'.join(pex.path() for pex in (reqs_pex, srcs_pex) if pex)
           builder = PEXBuilder(safe_path, interpreter, pex_info=pex_info)
           builder.freeze()
-
+      import pdb
+      pdb.set_trace()
       pex = PEX(exec_pex_path, interpreter)
 
       with self.context.new_workunit(name='eval',
```

and get the `exec_pex_path` to get the chroot, then run the PEX with your system's Python like `python2.7 <exec_pex_path>`.

 


",{},{}
