7278,IssuesEvent,2017-08-22 17:10:12+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,5776068,karelz,9141961,dotnet,closed,HttpClient throws WinHttpException,[],[],7,"# HttpClient throws WinHttpException

HttpClient GetAsync(...) fails with the inner exception message `The server returned an invalid or unrecognized response` when requesting https://www.cryptopia.co.nz/api/GetMarkets.

# General

When I retargeted to the .NET 4.5 framework I got a more detailed message `The server committed a protocol violation. Section=ResponseHeader Detail=CR must be followed by LF`. The server in question is Microsoft-IIS/10.0.

In the case of .NET 4.5 I got around the issue by add `<httpWebRequest useUnsafeHeaderParsing=""true"" />` to my `app.config` file. I know of no such option for dotnet core.

This issue is reproducible on dotnet core 2 preview 2 on Windows. Issue not reproducible on Linux and Mac.",{},{}
7319,IssuesEvent,2015-07-20 17:23:38+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,220205,jsha,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Client integration testing shouldn't use monolithic boulder binary,[],[],0,"Per https://github.com/letsencrypt/boulder/issues/482, the client integration test uses the boulder monolithic binary (start.sh). Instead it should use start.py, which runs the VA, SA, RA, CA, and WFE as separate processes and requires AMQP to talk between them. This is more consistent with the production environment and will help find bugs in the RPC code.",{},{}
