7740,IssuesEvent,2018-06-29 16:51:58+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,MBQI chokes on the first check of a model and runs out of memory,[],[],7,"Z3 version tested: 4.6.0 release 32-bit and 64-bit binaries for Windows

This script, which declares a function from 1-bit bit vectors to 1-bit bit vectors and asserts a couple properties on it, hangs while eating more and more RAM until it gives an out of memory error or access violation.

                (set-logic UFBV)
                (declare-fun n ((_ BitVec 1)) (_ BitVec 1))
                (assert (forall ((i (_ BitVec 1))) (= (n i) (ite (= i #b1) #b0 (n #b1)))))
                (assert (= (n #b0) #b0))
                (check-sat)


Apparently the tactics that Z3 uses for UFBV choke on this simple example. However, if the first line of the script is changed to (set-logic ALL), Z3 returns sat almost immediately. Other slight variants of this script can result in Z3 returning a result quickly, running out of memory, or hanging seemingly indefinitely while pinning a CPU core, depending on the input problem.

As a user who doesn't know much about how Z3 works internally, I find this particularly strange because the documentation at https://rise4fun.com/Z3/tutorial/guide seems to suggest that Z3 is complete for QBVF problems such as this because it can, in the worst case, flatten everything out into a SAT problem and solve that. Clearly this example should not generate a very large SAT problem!
",{},{}
