7880,IssuesEvent,2017-12-14 11:54:09+00:00,35872414,infoportugal/wagtail-modeltranslation,10087166,DiogoMarques29,12510303,infoportugal,closed,Original slug field language changes depending on editor's language,[],[],1,"Hi there,

I've noticed this issue when, by accident, I was using Wagtail admin's interface in the non-default language of my project and later noticed that my `{% slugurl 'slug_value' %}` statements ceased to work. Steps to reproduce this issue:

### 1. Using wagtail's admin interface in English

Save a page with `slug_en='english'` and `slug_en='portuguese'`.

Any declarations of `{% slugurl 'english' %}` will work in either language. In the database   `wagtailcore_page.slug` should read `'english'`.

### 2.  Using wagtail's admin interface in a different language (Portuguese for example)

Save the same page with exactly the same slugs (`slug_en='english'` and `slug_en='portuguese'`).

Declarations of `{% slugurl 'english' %}` break in both languages and `wagtailcore_page.slug` reads `'portuguese'`.


The behaviour above is consistent with `django-modeltranslation`'s [State of the Original Field](http://django-modeltranslation.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#the-state-of-the-original-field) but if editors of different languages are using/translating a wagtail website they will likely break any links relying on  `{% slugurl 'slug_value' %}`.

I suggest `wagtail-modeltranslation` works around this `django-modeltranslation` limitation and enforces a consistent slug value in the DB.
",{},{}
