8340,IssuesEvent,2016-09-19 11:56:54+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,21953319,hubertmis,16142269,openthread,opened,Possible vulnerability to replay attack in LinkAccept handler,[],[],0,"LinkAccept handler compares received Response TLV with both mChallenge (generated for multicast LinkRequest) and neighbor->mPending.mChallenge (generated for unicast LinkRequest).  If at least one of challenges matches Response TLV, LinkAccept message is accepted.

IMHO Response TLV should be compared with only one (appropriate) Challenge value and multicast mChallenge value should be invalidated after timeout to make sure replay attack is not possible.",{},{}
8373,IssuesEvent,2017-05-22 20:39:05+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,178376,beriberikix,16142269,openthread,opened,FR: Arduino support,"[{'id': 397568864, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/P3', 'name': 'P3', 'color': 'DFDF00', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Arduino has been a long-time ask as a supported framework. Most users just want a solution that allows them to hang a radio off an Uno, form a simple mesh and write some Processing code to blink lights/control motors/etc. I propose that an initial port would effectively be an NCP connected to an Arduino via serial and Arduino-inspired interface that maps to the CLI commands. Any OT-supported platform should work with the vanilla NCP build. For the actual API there is plenty of prior art in ""Arduino-esque"" networking: there's an official [Xbee shield](https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoWirelessShield) with 802.15.4 support that ""just works."" There's also an official WiFi library ([docs](https://www.arduino.cc/en/Reference/WiFi), [code](https://github.com/arduino/Arduino/tree/master/libraries/WiFi)) with a richer interface. With the [porting guide](https://github.com/openthread/openthread/wiki/Porting-Guide) we should be in a better position to develop this port. Also, Arduino now supports [CI](https://github.com/arduino/arduino-builder/wiki/Doing-continuous-integration-with-arduino-builder) so we can run tests against the port as OT evolves.

FWIW, the [FRDM-KW41Z](http://www.nxp.com/products/software-and-tools/hardware-development-tools/freedom-development-boards/nxp-freedom-development-kit-for-kinetis-kw41z-31z-21z-mcus:FRDM-KW41Z) would make for an ideal reference platform since it is in the form factor of a Shield. ",{},{}
8380,IssuesEvent,2016-02-28 21:24:31+00:00,32363483,python-escpos/python-escpos,17401709,Loafdude,16302939,python-escpos,opened,Feature: Add optional timeout variable for network connections,[],[],0,"I needed to shorten the timeout for printers to return to the user more quickly.

I'm not familiar with merges etc sorry. Thought I would share maybe make it into dev branch

printer.py line 155

    def __init__(self, host, port=9100, timeout=60, *args, **kwargs):
        """"""

        :param host : Printer's hostname or IP address
        :param port : Port to write to
        """"""
        Escpos.__init__(self, *args, **kwargs)
        self.host = host
        self.port = port
        self.timeout = timeout
        self.open()

    def open(self):
        """""" Open TCP socket with ``socket``-library and set it as escpos device """"""
        self.device = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
        self.device.settimeout(self.timeout)
        self.device.connect((self.host, self.port))

        if self.device is None:
            print(""Could not open socket for {0}"".format(self.host))

